    {
      "index": 2,
      "label": "02 Geographic vs Diagrammatic",
      "screenshot": "slides/slide-02.png",
      "background": "#FFFFFF",
      "layout": "two-column",
      "elements": [
        {
          "type": "text", "id": "title",
          "text": "Geographic vs Diagrammatic",
          "x": 86, "y": 72, "width": 1748,
          "font": "EB Garamond", "size": 58, "weight": 700, "color": "#0B1B33"
        },
        {
          "type": "text", "id": "subtitle",
          "text": "Two ways to represent a transit network — one truthful to the land, the other truthful to the rider.",
          "x": 86, "y": 160, "width": 1748,
          "font": "Calibri", "style": "italic", "size": 26, "color": "#5A6B82"
        },
        {
          "type": "rect", "id": "divider",
          "x": 960, "y": 288, "width": 2, "height": 712,
          "fill": "#E8EAEE"
        },
        {
          "type": "text", "id": "left-era",
          "text": "BEFORE 1933",
          "x": 86, "y": 288, "font": "Calibri", "size": 24, "weight": 700,
          "color": "#DC241F", "letterSpacing": 6
        },
        {
          "type": "text", "id": "left-head",
          "text": "Geographic Maps",
          "x": 86, "y": 322, "width": 840,
          "font": "EB Garamond", "size": 44, "weight": 700, "color": "#0B1B33"
        },
        {
          "type": "text", "id": "left-body",
          "text": "The Underground was drawn on top of London's streets. Stations in the centre huddled together in an unreadable knot; suburban stations floated in near-empty space.\n\nF. H. Stingemore's 1932 map — the last of the geographic era — tried to compensate by slightly enlarging central London, but the fundamental problem remained: passengers don't navigate by longitude.",
          "x": 86, "y": 432, "width": 840,
          "font": "Calibri", "size": 24, "color": "#0B1B33", "lineHeight": 1.55
        },
        {
          "type": "bulletList", "id": "left-bullets",
          "x": 86, "y": 720, "width": 840,
          "font": "Calibri", "size": 24, "color": "#5A6B82",
          "items": ["True to the city", "Central stations crowded together", "Line colours obscured by streets"]
        },
        {
          "type": "text", "id": "right-era",
          "text": "FROM 1933",
          "x": 1003, "y": 288, "font": "Calibri", "size": 24, "weight": 700,
          "color": "#1C3F95", "letterSpacing": 6
        },
        {
          "type": "text", "id": "right-head",
          "text": "Beck's Diagram",
          "x": 1003, "y": 322, "width": 840,
          "font": "EB Garamond", "size": 44, "weight": 700, "color": "#0B1B33"
        },
        {
          "type": "text", "id": "right-body",
          "text": "Harry Beck — inspired by electrical schematics he'd drawn as a signalling draughtsman — discarded geography entirely. Lines became horizontals, verticals, and 45° diagonals. Stations were evenly spaced.\n\nHe understood that passengers, once underground, don't care about compass directions. They care about which line to board, which station to change at, and how many stops until home.",
          "x": 1003, "y": 432, "width": 840,
          "font": "Calibri", "size": 24, "color": "#0B1B33", "lineHeight": 1.55
        },
        {
          "type": "bulletList", "id": "right-bullets",
          "x": 1003, "y": 720, "width": 840,
          "font": "Calibri", "size": 24, "color": "#5A6B82",
          "items": ["True to the journey", "Evenly spaced stations", "Lines instantly recognisable by colour"]
        }
      ],
      "speakerNotes": "To understand what Beck did, you first have to understand what came before him. Until 1933, every Underground map was a geographic map..."
    },
    {
      "index": 3,
      "label": "03 The Electrical Circuit",
      "screenshot": "slides/slide-03.png",
      "background": "#FFFFFF",
      "layout": "text-left-image-right",
      "elements": [
        {
          "type": "image", "id": "photo",
          "src": "media/image-3-1.jpg",
          "x": 1080, "y": 0, "width": 840, "height": 1080,
          "objectFit": "cover",
          "alt": "District line train at Sloane Square station"
        },
        {
          "type": "text", "id": "slide-num",
          "text": "02", "x": 86, "y": 72,
          "font": "Calibri", "size": 24, "weight": 700,
          "color": "#DC241F", "letterSpacing": 8
        },
        {
          "type": "text", "id": "title",
          "text": "The Electrical Circuit",
          "x": 86, "y": 120, "width": 936,
          "font": "EB Garamond", "size": 72, "weight": 700, "color": "#0B1B33"
        },
        {
          "type": "text", "id": "body1",
          "text": "Beck trained as a signalling engineer. He drew circuits for a living — grids of components connected by orthogonal lines, where topology mattered but exact position did not.",
          "x": 86, "y": 310, "width": 890,
          "font": "Calibri", "size": 30, "color": "#0B1B33", "lineHeight": 1.55
        },
        {
          "type": "text", "id": "body2",
          "text": "When he sketched his 1931 prototype during a layoff, he applied the same logic to the Tube. Passengers, he reasoned, are electrons: what matters is the network they traverse, not the map coordinates they pass through.\n\nThe initial submission was rejected as \"too revolutionary.\" A 500-copy trial run in 1932 proved the public disagreed with management.",
          "x": 86, "y": 560, "width": 890,
          "font": "Calibri", "size": 24, "color": "#5A6B82", "lineHeight": 1.6
        }
      ],
      "speakerNotes": "Here's the photograph that in some ways explains everything. This is a District line train at Sloane Square station..."
    },
    {
      "index": 4,
      "label": "04 Four Principles of the Diagram",
      "screenshot": "slides/slide-04.png",
      "background": "#F5F1E8",
      "layout": "2x2-cards",
      "elements": [
        {
          "type": "text", "id": "title",
          "text": "Four Principles of the Diagram",
          "x": 86, "y": 65, "width": 1748,
          "font": "EB Garamond", "size": 56, "weight": 700, "color": "#0B1B33"
        },
        {
          "type": "text", "id": "subtitle",
          "text": "The rules Beck imposed — and the compromises they forced.",
          "x": 86, "y": 152, "width": 1748,
          "font": "Calibri", "style": "italic", "size": 26, "color": "#5A6B82"
        },
        {
          "type": "card", "id": "card-1",
          "x": 107, "y": 235, "width": 828, "height": 368,
          "background": "#FFFFFF", "border": "#E8EAEE",
          "accentColor": "#E32017", "accentWidth": 12,
          "number": "01", "title": "Orthogonality",
          "body": "Every line segment runs horizontally, vertically, or at exactly 45°. No curves. No arbitrary angles. The system's grammar reduces to three directions."
        },
        {
          "type": "card", "id": "card-2",
          "x": 985, "y": 235, "width": 828, "height": 368,
          "background": "#FFFFFF", "border": "#E8EAEE",
          "accentColor": "#003688", "accentWidth": 12,
          "number": "02", "title": "Even Spacing",
          "body": "Stations along a line are placed at roughly equal intervals regardless of real distance. A stop is a stop; its significance to the rider is not measured in metres."
        },
        {
          "type": "card", "id": "card-3",
          "x": 107, "y": 645, "width": 828, "height": 368,
          "background": "#FFFFFF", "border": "#E8EAEE",
          "accentColor": "#0098D4", "accentWidth": 12,
          "number": "03", "title": "Colour Per Line",
          "body": "Each line gets one distinctive colour, applied consistently across the entire network. The Central is red. The Piccadilly is navy. Identity is instantaneous."
        },
        {
          "type": "card", "id": "card-4",
          "x": 985, "y": 645, "width": 828, "height": 368,
          "background": "#FFFFFF", "border": "#E8EAEE",
          "accentColor": "#B36305", "accentWidth": 12,
          "number": "04", "title": "One Topographical Feature",
          "body": "Only the Thames survives from the geographic map, schematised into a stylised ribbon. Its role: orient the rider at a glance — north bank or south."
        }
      ],
      "speakerNotes": "Four constraints define the diagram. First — orthogonality..."
    },
    {
