    {
      "index": 10,
      "label": "10 The Map Rewired London",
      "screenshot": "slides/slide-10.png",
      "background": "#0B1B33",
      "layout": "quote-with-fact-row",
      "elements": [
        {
          "type": "text", "id": "eyebrow",
          "text": "LEGACY",
          "x": 100, "y": 72,
          "font": "Calibri", "size": 24, "weight": 700,
          "color": "#C9D4E8", "letterSpacing": 8
        },
        {
          "type": "text", "id": "title",
          "text": "The Map Rewired London",
          "x": 100, "y": 120, "width": 1720,
          "font": "EB Garamond", "size": 60, "weight": 700, "color": "#FFFFFF"
        },
        {
          "type": "rect", "id": "rule",
          "x": 100, "y": 240, "width": 80, "height": 5, "fill": "#DC241F"
        },
        {
          "type": "text", "id": "quote",
          "text": "\"The positive image Beck provided encouraged more people to use the Underground … but the effect was also to change users' mental maps of London — affecting their geographical understanding of the city. Distance, direction and existence all get distorted and continue to do so today.\"",
          "x": 100, "y": 280, "width": 1720,
          "font": "EB Garamond", "style": "italic", "size": 42,
          "color": "#DCE3F1", "lineHeight": 1.55
        },
        {
          "type": "richText", "id": "attribution",
          "x": 100, "y": 700, "width": 1720,
          "runs": [
            { "text": "Alexander J. Kent", "weight": 700, "color": "#C9D4E8", "size": 24 },
            { "text": " — Reader in Cartography, Canterbury Christ Church University", "color": "#7A8CAB", "size": 24 }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "rect", "id": "divider",
          "x": 100, "y": 750, "width": 1720, "height": 1, "fill": "#FFFFFF", "opacity": 0.12
        },
        {
          "type": "factRow", "id": "facts",
          "x": 100, "y": 790, "width": 1720,
          "facts": [
            { "label": "PREDECESSORS", "text": "Max Gill removed topographic detail. Fred Stingemore added Johnston font and distorted the network. Beck inherited their work and pushed it to its logical conclusion." },
            { "label": "USER-CENTRED",  "text": "Beck was himself a commuter. He stripped away what a map \"should\" be in favour of what riders actually needed: a clear route planner, nothing more." },
            { "label": "AFTER BECK",    "text": "He continued refining the map until 1959. He also designed posters, drew cartoons for the staff magazine, and tutored typography. He died in 1974." }
          ],
          "labelColor": "#DC241F", "textColor": "#C9D4E8", "labelSize": 24, "textSize": 26
        }
      ],
      "speakerNotes": "Beck didn't invent from nothing, and his map didn't just help people navigate — it changed how they understood the city itself..."
    },
